USA Gymnastics supports the letter from the U.S. Olympic Committee and recognizes the absolute necessity for the Olympic community to work together to create a safe environment for all its athletes.
We agree with what the USOC has said, namely that the interests of our athletes and our clubs, and of their sport, can be better served by bringing about a significant change within our organization, and not by decertification.
USA Gymnastics has promoted an independent investigation to understand how it was possible that an abuse of the dimensions described with so much courage by those who have managed to survive Larry Nassar has remained hidden for so long, and is willing to implement any necessary or appropriate change.
USA Gymnastics and USOC have the same goal: to make gymnastics and other sports as safe as possible so that athletes can pursue their dreams in a reliable, positive and responsible environment.
During the 1960s, Brzezinski was a foreign policy adviser to John F. Kennedy and later to the Lyndon B. Johnson administration.
During the 1976 elections, he advised Carter on foreign policy and then served as National Security Advisor (NSA) from 1977 to 1981, succeeding Henry Kissinger.
As a member of the National Security Council, he worked with Carter on the diplomatic management of international affairs, including the Camp David Accords of 1978, the normalization of relations between China and the United States in the late 1970s, the Iranian Revolution (which led to the Iran hostage crisis in 1979), and the Soviet invasion of Afghanistan in 1979.
