This not only confirms that some dinosaurs had feathers, a theory already widely disseminated, but provides more details than fossils, such as color and three-dimensional arrangement.
According to scientists, the plumage of this animal was brownish in the upper part, with a pale or carotenoid coloration in the lower part.
The discovery also allows to obtain detailed information about the evolution of bird feathers.
Since the feathers of the dinosaur are not equipped with the basic structure, the so-called spine, but instead have other typical characteristics of feathers, barbs and barbules, the researchers have concluded that the spine is probably the result of a subsequent evolutionary development of such characteristics.
The structure of the feathers suggests that they were not used for flight, but rather for temperature regulation or courtship. The researchers hypothesize that, although it is the tail of a young dinosaur, the specimen shows adult feathers and not the down of a chick.
According to the researchers' hypotheses, despite the tail belonging to a young dinosaur, the specimen reveals a feathering from an adult specimen and not that of a chick.
